# üöÄ Proxmox Home Lab Setup and Troubleshooting Guide  

## üõ†Ô∏è The Problem  
When setting up Proxmox on my Dell 5450, I encountered multiple networking issues while trying to access the web interface. Additionally, my ASUS Zephyrus laptop does not have a built-in Ethernet port, so I had to connect the Dell 5450 through an Ethernet cable plugged into my USB-C dock. Initially, the connection wasn‚Äôt established, and I couldn‚Äôt reach the Proxmox web interface.

---

## üîç Investigation and Solution  

### 1Ô∏è‚É£ Ethernet Setup and Dock Issue  
Since my ASUS doesn‚Äôt have an Ethernet port, I used a USB-C dock to connect my Dell 5450 to Ethernet. I assigned static IP addresses to both devices to create a direct connection.  

**Troubleshooting steps:**  
- Verified Ethernet link status on both the Dell 5450 and ASUS.  
- Checked the `/etc/network/interfaces` configuration on the Dell 5450.  
- Ensured that `pveproxy` service was active and port 8006 was listening.  
- Verified the network connectivity using `ping`.

### 2Ô∏è‚É£ Network Configuration  
I edited the `/etc/network/interfaces` file to set up a static IP for the Dell 5450:  

```bash
auto enp0s31f6  
iface enp0s31f6 inet static  
  address 10.0.0.200  
  netmask 255.255.255.0  
  gateway 10.0.0.1  
Then, I restarted the networking service:

bash
Copy
Edit
systemctl restart networking
3Ô∏è‚É£ Verifying Service Status
I confirmed that the pveproxy service was running and port 8006 was open:

bash
Copy
Edit
systemctl status pveproxy
netstat -tulnp | grep 8006
4Ô∏è‚É£ Accessing Proxmox Web Interface
Once everything was configured, I opened the Proxmox web interface at https://10.0.0.200:8006. Initially, I received a security warning in the browser due to a self-signed certificate, but after bypassing it, I was able to log in successfully.

‚úÖ Final Outcome
I successfully accessed the Proxmox web interface and completed the setup.

